definition.value: The process by which an organism becomes pregnant.
The fertilization of two or more ova by sperm from separate acts of sexual intercourse, which can lead to twins with different fathers.
Impregnation in addition to a prior impregnation.
A transgender person who is incarcerated, typically in a prison.
A non-specialized physician.
Physician trained in medical specialty; that is, a branch of medical practice that is focused on a defined group of patients, diseases, skills, or philosophy.
A physician who specializes in childbirth.
Surgeon trained in a specific surgical specialty; that is, a branch of surgical practice that is focused on a defined group of patients, diseases, skills, or philosophy.
A surgeon specializing in otorhinolaryngology; that is, conditions of the ear, nose, and throat (ENT) and related structures of the head and neck.
A non-specialized surgeon.

Sexual repression is a state in which a person is prevented from expressing their own sexuality. Sexual repression is often associated with feelings of guilt or shame being associated with sexual impulses. What constitutes sexual repression is subjective and can vary greatly between cultures and moral systems.
A drug adverse event that is caused by a drug administration.
A transgender person who is Latine.
Condition in which individuals desire to be disabled or having discomfort with being able-bodied beginning in early adolescence and resulting in harmful consequences.

People who have body integrity dysphoria have oftentimes been incorrectly compared to transgender people who seek surgery as both user similar metaphors to describe their conditions: "born into the wrong body" and "having a part not of their true self", for instance. This may have led to the coining of "body integrity dysphoria" (being akin to gender dysphoria). However, it is important to consider major differences between the two, including the major umbrellla of transgender identity entirely unconnected to surgical procedures and the kinds of procedures undergone by transgender people and the reasonings for them undergoing such procedures.

Note that some who experience "body integrity dysphoria" may utilize terminology such as "transabled", "transability", or "transableism". Depending on context, this may be considered offensive and appropriative when considering persons with disabilities.
It has been suggested that, because the dysphoric aspects of "body integrity dysphoria" do not tend to outweigh amputation desire, that "dysphoria" may not be an adequate term for this condition.
Dysphoria associated with the feeling that one's body is of the wrong species.

"Species dysphoria" is not a medical diagnosis and is not recognized by DSM-5. It is merely a descriptive label used by otherkin and therians. Often transphobic sources may compare species dysphoria to gender dysphoria, although these two concepts are ostensibly unrelated.
Social communication is the use of language in social contexts.
External manifestation of gender identity.
Gender expression is often codified by gendered clothing (or lack thereof) and other gender-based expectations relating to appearance, such as consistent cosmetic use.
Having an identity considered female.
Having an identity considered male.
Usage of masculine, feminine, other gendered, ungendered, and ambiguous clothing, behavior, posture, mannerisms, speech patterns, and activites, among other things.
Usage of clothing, behavior, posture, mannerisms, speech patterns, and activites, among other things, to indicate a female gender identity or gender role.
Usage of clothing, behavior, posture, mannerisms, speech patterns, and activites, among other things, to indicate a male gender identity or gender role.

Transgender people have a gender identity or gender expression that differs from their assigned sex. In some select cases, transgender people are sometimes called transsexual if they desire medical assistance to transition from one sex to another. "Transgender" is also an umbrella term: in addition to including people whose gender identity is the opposite of their assigned sex (trans men and trans women), it may include people who are not exclusively masculine or feminine (people who are genderqueer or non-binary, including bigender, pangender, genderfluid, or agender). Other definitions of transgender also include people who belong to a third gender, or else conceptualize transgender people as a third gender.
Having a gender (identity) which is different from the sex one was assigned at birth: being assigned male at birth but having a female gender or vice versa; or, pertaining to such people.

Not identifying with culturally conventional gender roles and categories of male or female; having changed gender identity from male to female or female to male, or identifying with elements of both, or having some other gender identity; or, pertaining to such people.
"Transgender" is an adjective and should not be formed into a collective noun. This terminology is often used by anti-transgender activists aiming to dehumanize transgender people.

"Transgender" and its derivatives ("transgender male", "transgender female", "transgender woman", "transgender man", etc.) are generally not considered genders and/or gender identities. Listing "male" separate from "transgender male" or listing "transgender" separate from "male"/"female" is transphobic in the sense that it denies a transgender person's gender, forcing them to choose in an unclear situation, and implies that they are somehow deviant from "normal" maleness/femaleness. A few transgender persons still utilize these terms in identifying, however, but an "other (please specify)" option is much more functional in this regard (as well as a "select all that apply" for gender/gender identity).
The adjective "transgender" should never have an extraneous "-ed" attached to it. This is confusing and grammatically unnecessary.
Any detectable and heritable change in the genetic material that causes a change in the genotype and which is transmitted to daughter cells and to succeeding generations.

A reduced ability to secrete gonadotropins, which are protein hormones secreted by gonadotrope cells of the anterior pituitary gland, including the hormones follitropin (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).
A parent of a transgender person.
The determination of an infant's gender shortly after birth.
The determination of an infant's sex shortly after birth.
Biological sex is the quality of a biological organism based on reproductive function or organs.
In general, the term "biological sex" should be avoided, especially in medical contexts. Instead, more specific terms such as "chromosomal sex" should be utilized.
Sex as determined by genotypic qualities, namely chromosomal or genetic factors.
Sex as determined by phenotypic qualities, namely primary and/or secondary sex characteristics.
A parent of an LGBTQIA+ person.
The establishment of sex by a non-genetic cue, such as nutrient availability, experienced within a discrete period after conception.
Establishment of sex at conception by genetic factors such as sex chromosomes.

Intersex is an umbrella term with a complex history. It is usually used to refer to persons with congenital conditions which involve differences in the many intertwined processes of sexual development.

It is important to note that some transgender persons are intersex, but not all, and vice versa. Terms like "ultergender" and "ipsogender" help clarify the ways these terms might overlap. While some studies have purported that small segments of the trans community might have traits that some consider intersex, the association of transgender with intersex in absolutes is often linked to transmedicalist ideologies. The Transgender Professional Association for Transgender Health (TPATH) notes in its guidelines: "While it may be appropriate to discuss intersections of intersex and trans experience, please do not erase the specificity of intersex experiences, for instance through conflating intersex with trans... In discussing these issues, we ask that endosexual transgender (i.e. not intersex) participants recognize their privilege in, for instance, not having faced the risk of infant genital mutilation or other non-consensual medical interventions during childhood."
Any of various surgeries which aim to masculinize the chest region.
An intersex person with a male gender identity.
An intersex person with a female gender identity.
Sex as determined by the presence of particular sex chromosomes or combinations of sex chromosomes, without regard to phenotypic manifestations.

It is almost always preferable to include the specific karyotype (XX, XY, etc.) rather than "chromosomal male" or "chromosomal female". Additionally, avoid usage unless the patient's karyotype is actually known and confirmed via laboratory reports.
Sex as determined by the presence and/or activation of particular genes or combinations of genes, without regard to phenotypic manifestations.
A biological system that determines the development of sexual characteristics in an organism.

A system that determines the sex of offspring among most arachnids, almost all apterygote and paleopteran insects, most exoptergote insects, and some nematodes, crustaceans, gastropod molluscs, and bony fish. In this system, there is only one sex chromosome, referred to as X. Males only have one X chromosome (X0), while females have two (XX).

The sex-determination system found in humans, most other mammals, some insects (Drosophila), some snakes, and some plants (Ginkgo). In this system, the sex of an individual is determined by a pair of sex chromosomes. Females typically have two of the same kind of sex chromosome (XX), and are called the homogametic sex. Males typically have two different kinds of sex chromosomes (XY), and are called the heterogametic sex.
A system that determines the sex of offspring in several moths. In those species, males have two Z chromosomes whereas females have one.

A chromosomal system that determines the sex of offspring in birds, some fish and crustaceans such as the giant river prawn, some insects (including butterflies and moths), and some reptiles, including Komodo dragons. In this system, female has a pair of dissimilar ZW chromosomes and male has two similar ZZ chromosomes.
A type of environmental sex determination in which the temperatures experienced during embryonic/larval development determine the sex of the offspring.

A sex-determination system in which males develop from unfertilized eggs and are haploid, and females develop from fertilized eggs and are diploid. Haplodiploidy determines the sex in all members of the insect orders Hymenoptera (bees, ants, and wasps) and Thysanoptera ('thrips'). The system also occurs sporadically in some spider mites, Hemiptera, Coleoptera (bark beetles), and rotifers.

A gender (or gender marker) assigned by any of various persons or organizations other than an individual themselves; such a term is usually shortened from "assigned gender at birth" (assigned gender at birth is preferable in these situations for the sake of specificity).
An assignment of a female gender shortly after birth.
An assignment of a male gender shortly after birth.
